1ï¸âƒ£ Core Teaching (Simple, Exam-Oriented)
ğŸ”¹ What are Mahajanapadas?

Around 6th century BCE, tribal society transformed into territorial states due to:

Expansion of agriculture

Use of iron tools

Growth of trade & towns

This led to the rise of 16 Mahajanapadas.

Examples:

Magadha

Kosala

Avanti

Vatsa

Kuru

Gandhara

ğŸ“Œ UPSC Focus:
Why Magadha became powerful, not the full list.

ğŸ”¹ Why Magadha Became Powerful?

Fertile Gangetic plains

Iron ores (weapons, tools)

Strong rulers (Bimbisara, Ajatashatru)

Strategic capitals: Rajgir, Pataliputra

ğŸ”¹ Religious Background (6th Century BCE)

Excessive Vedic rituals

Dominance of Brahmins

Expensive sacrifices

Social inequality

ğŸ‘‰ Result: Rise of new religious movements

ğŸ”µ Jainism
Founder

Mahavira (24th Tirthankara)

Core Principles

Ahimsa (non-violence)

Satya (truth)

Asteya (non-stealing)

Brahmacharya

Aparigraha (non-possession)

Key Points

Rejected Vedas

No creator God

Stressed severe asceticism

ğŸŸ  Buddhism
Founder

Gautama Buddha

Four Noble Truths

Life is full of suffering

Desire causes suffering

Suffering can end

Eightfold Path leads to liberation

Eightfold Path

Right view, intention, speech, action, livelihood, effort, mindfulness, concentration

Key Points

Middle Path (avoid extremes)

Rejected caste discrimination

Used Pali language

Sangha system

ğŸ“Œ UPSC Focus:
Comparison: Buddhism vs Jainism, causes of rise, social impact.

